The problem of finding the longest common subsequence is a classic problem in computer science, and this paper proposes a generalization of the problem to finding the longest common subsequence in k-length substrings. This problem is motivated by computational biology, which suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. The paper proposes several algorithms that make use of dynamic programming, sparse dynamic programming, and tabulation, which are techniques commonly used in the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-categories. Finally, the paper also makes use of linear-time and linear-space preprocessing, which is a technique commonly used in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DS, cs.CC, cs.DM, cs.CG, and cs.LG, in that order.
